WEBVTT

00:00:01.920 --> 00:00:08.640
<v Teacher>So, I want us to run through the forms of <b>haber</b>, this <i>to have</i> that we use to go into the past.

00:00:08.820 --> 00:00:14.180
<v Teacher>We said that we can remember them by looking at the two vowel sounds that we have inside the word <b>haber</b>.

00:00:14.180 --> 00:00:17.060
<v Teacher>So give me <i>I have</i> and <i>we have</i>:

00:00:17.699 --> 00:00:19.380
<v Student><b>He</b> and <b>hemos</b>.

00:00:19.380 --> 00:00:19.699
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:19.699 --> 00:00:23.779
<v Teacher>And give me the rest of the versions.

00:00:23.779 --> 00:00:26.340
<v Student><b>Ha</b>, <b>has</b>, <b>han</b>.

00:00:26.340 --> 00:00:27.300
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:32.200
<v Teacher>We said that nouns ending A are feminine nouns.

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:36.680
<v Teacher>So, for example, <i>the house</i> - <b>la casa</b>.

00:00:36.680 --> 00:00:39.480
<v Teacher>So words ending A are feminine, but

00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:44.399
<v Teacher>Words ending MA are masculine.

00:00:44.399 --> 00:00:49.360
<v Teacher>There's a small group of words that end MA which are masculine words.

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:54.480
<v Teacher>For example, <i>the problem</i> in Spanish is <b>el problema</b>.

00:00:54.579 --> 00:00:55.940
<v Student><b>El problema</b>.

00:00:55.940 --> 00:00:56.820
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:56.820 --> 00:00:58.339
<v Teacher>How would you say?

00:00:58.339 --> 00:01:01.219
<v Teacher>Have you understood the problem?

00:01:01.219 --> 00:01:03.699
<v Teacher>Have you understood the problem?

00:01:03.699 --> 00:01:05.860
<v Teacher>What was to understand?

00:01:06.600 --> 00:01:07.960
<v Student><b>Comprender</b>.

00:01:07.960 --> 00:01:08.760
<v Teacher><b>Comprender</b>.

00:01:08.760 --> 00:01:09.000
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:10.680
<v Teacher>We can use Comprender.

00:01:10.680 --> 00:01:13.080
<v Teacher>Or we can use <b>entender</b>.

00:01:13.080 --> 00:01:15.800
<v Teacher>But <b>comprender</b> is perfect here as well.

00:01:15.800 --> 00:01:17.880
<v Teacher>Have you understood the problem?

00:01:17.880 --> 00:01:19.000
<v Teacher>And let's talk

00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:23.080
<v Teacher>formally, to <b>usted</b>.

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:26.360
<v Student>¿<b>Ha entendido el problema</b>?

00:01:26.360 --> 00:01:26.920
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:30.440
<v Teacher>¿<b>Ha entendido el problema</b>?

00:01:30.440 --> 00:01:31.160
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:30.960 --> 00:01:36.160
<v Teacher>So a very common error for people learning Spanish is to say la problema.

00:01:36.160 --> 00:01:39.520
<v Teacher>Now if we look at why these words ending M-A

00:01:39.880 --> 00:01:44.040
<v Teacher>are actually masculine is going to help us internalize it.

00:01:44.040 --> 00:01:47.720
<v Teacher>So these words the M the M A actually come from Greek.

00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:50.760
<v Teacher><b>Problema</b> in Greek is <b>provlima</b>.

00:01:50.759 --> 00:01:54.200
<v Teacher><i>System</i> in Greek is <b>systima</b>.

00:01:54.200 --> 00:01:57.399
<v Teacher>In Spanish, it's <b>sistema</b>.

00:01:57.399 --> 00:01:59.880
<v Teacher>So how would you say the system?

00:02:00.060 --> 00:02:01.500
<v Student><b>El sistema</b>.

00:02:01.500 --> 00:02:02.700
<v Teacher><b>El sistema</b>.

00:02:02.700 --> 00:02:03.660
<v Teacher>So it's <b>el</b>.

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:06.140
<v Teacher>Now in Greek these words are neuter words.

00:02:06.140 --> 00:02:09.420
<v Teacher>In Greek you have masculine, feminine, and neuter.

00:02:09.240 --> 00:02:13.080
<v Teacher>And neutral words in Greek look like masculine words.

00:02:13.080 --> 00:02:15.640
<v Teacher>They have a similar word for the.

00:02:15.640 --> 00:02:17.800
<v Teacher>They look kind of like masculine words.

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:19.080
<v Teacher>So when they went in

00:02:19.260 --> 00:02:23.340
<v Teacher>to Spanish or into Latin, they could mistaken as masculine words.

00:02:23.340 --> 00:02:28.380
<v Teacher>So if we can identify them, there's a key group of words we can avoid committing this error with.

00:02:28.380 --> 00:02:29.580
<v Teacher>If it ends M A

00:02:30.240 --> 00:02:33.120
<v Teacher>It's probably from Greek and probably masculine.

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:35.600
<v Teacher>So how would you say the system again?

00:02:35.920 --> 00:02:37.280
<v Student><b>El sistema</b>.

00:02:37.280 --> 00:02:38.640
<v Teacher><b>El sistema</b>.

00:02:38.640 --> 00:02:40.960
<v Teacher>How would you say have you understood the system?

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:42.160
<v Teacher>Talking informally.

00:02:42.160 --> 00:02:44.320
<v Teacher>Have you understood the system?

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:48.280
<v Student>¿<b>Has entendido el sistema</b>?

00:02:48.280 --> 00:02:48.680
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:48.760 --> 00:02:50.840
<v Teacher>¿<b>Has entendido el sistema</b>?

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:51.720
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:51.720 --> 00:02:53.640
<v Teacher><b>Sentir</b>, in Spanish.

00:02:53.640 --> 00:02:56.519
<v Teacher><b>Sentir</b> is <i>to feel</i>.

00:02:56.420 --> 00:03:00.580
<v Teacher>Related to <i>sensation</i>, so <b>sentir</b>, <i>to feel</i>.

00:03:00.580 --> 00:03:04.740
<v Teacher>And you can also use it like to perceive in the sense of smell.

00:03:04.740 --> 00:03:09.860
<v Teacher>So if you wanted to ask for example, have you felt the aroma?

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:13.000
<v Teacher>It would be a way of asking, have you smelt the aroma?

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:14.200
<v Teacher>Have you felt it?

00:03:14.200 --> 00:03:15.480
<v Teacher>So how would you say that?

00:03:15.480 --> 00:03:18.120
<v Teacher>Have you felt the aroma?

00:03:19.700 --> 00:03:23.540
<v Student>¿<b>Has sentido el aroma</b>?

00:03:23.540 --> 00:03:24.260
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:26.980
<v Teacher>¿<b>Has sentido el aroma</b>?

00:03:26.980 --> 00:03:27.460
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:27.460 --> 00:03:29.380
<v Teacher>So el again.

00:03:29.240 --> 00:03:43.960
<v Teacher>So we have <b>el</b>: <b>el problema</b>, <b>el sistema</b>, <b>el programa</b>, <b>el aroma</b>, <b>el panorama</b>. <b>El clima</b>, which is a little bit different in English, which means <i>climate</i>, <b>el clima</b>. And some others.

00:03:44.640 --> 00:03:48.240
<v Teacher>Have you understood the program?

00:03:48.240 --> 00:03:51.360
<v Student>¿<b>Has entendido el programa</b>?

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:51.920
<v Teacher>Good.

00:03:51.920 --> 00:03:55.360
<v Teacher>Again, how was <i>to lose</i>? (Perishable)

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:56.400
<v Student>Perdir.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:57.400
<v Teacher>Close.

00:03:57.400 --> 00:03:58.400
<v Student><b>Perder</b>.

00:03:58.400 --> 00:04:00.080
<v Teacher><b>Perder</b>. Good. So how would you say <i>I have lost</i>?

00:04:00.080 --> 00:04:04.080
<v Student><b>He perdido</b>.

00:04:04.080 --> 00:04:05.520
<v Teacher>Good. Now what if you wanted to emphasize <i>I have lost</i>?

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:09.440
<v Student><b>Yo he perdido</b>.

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:10.500
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:10.500 --> 00:04:12.099
<v Teacher>Now if you want to say <i>I have got lost</i>, <i>I have got lost</i>,

00:04:12.099 --> 00:04:12.819
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:12.819 --> 00:04:18.419
<v Teacher>Now if you want to say I have got lost, I've got lost

00:04:18.639 --> 00:04:20.400
<v Teacher>You can just say I've lost myself.

00:04:20.400 --> 00:04:23.440
<v Teacher>We said I get ready is I prepare myself.

00:04:23.440 --> 00:04:24.720
<v Teacher><b>Me preparo</b>.

00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:27.280
<v Teacher>We don't use this in Spanish, <i>I get ready</i>.

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:29.040
<v Teacher>You say <i>I ready myself</i>.

00:04:29.220 --> 00:04:30.419
<v Teacher><b>Me preparo</b>.

00:04:30.419 --> 00:04:34.340
<v Teacher>So you don't say I get lost or I have got lost.

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:36.580
<v Teacher>You say I have lost myself.

00:04:36.580 --> 00:04:38.180
<v Teacher>So how would you say that?

00:04:39.099 --> 00:04:40.300
<v Student><b>Me he perdido</b>.

00:04:40.300 --> 00:04:41.500
<v Teacher>Again.

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:43.500
<v Student><b>Me he perdido</b>.

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:49.819
<v Teacher>Yes, when you say it fluently, it doesn't actually sound any different, which is why I asked for again to make sure that you were putting it.

00:04:49.819 --> 00:04:51.020
<v Teacher>Because the /<i>e</i>/

00:04:51.039 --> 00:04:53.280
<v Teacher>of <b>me</b> and the /<i>e</i>/ of <b>he</b>

00:04:53.520 --> 00:04:54.720
<v Teacher>will blend together.

00:04:54.720 --> 00:04:56.240
<v Teacher><b>Me he perdido</b>.

00:04:57.120 --> 00:05:00.319
<v Teacher>So that means I have lost myself or I've got lost.

00:05:00.319 --> 00:05:05.759
<v Teacher>Now what if you wanted to be emphatic as well and say I have lost myself?

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:07.840
<v Student><b>Yo me he perdido</b>.

00:05:07.840 --> 00:05:08.240
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:08.240 --> 00:05:10.000
<v Teacher><b>Yo me he perdido</b>.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.720
<v Teacher>How is you have lost?

00:05:12.720 --> 00:05:14.800
<v Teacher>Speaking informally.

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:17.360
<v Student><b>Has perdido</b>.

00:05:17.360 --> 00:05:17.760
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:18.880
<v Teacher><b>Has perdido</b>.

00:05:18.880 --> 00:05:27.440
<v Teacher>We said that the word for you in the sense of you lose, you see, not I see you, but you see.

00:05:26.860 --> 00:05:29.020
<v Teacher>is <b>tú</b> for informal <i>you</i>: <b>tú</b>, <i>t-u</i>.

00:05:29.020 --> 00:05:30.300
<v Student><b>Tú</b>.

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:36.460
<v Teacher>So how would you say you have lost being emphatic?

00:05:37.080 --> 00:05:38.840
<v Student><b>Tú ha perdido</b>.

00:05:38.840 --> 00:05:41.000
<v Teacher>There's a bit of a contradiction there.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:42.600
<v Student><b>Tú has perdido</b>.

00:05:42.600 --> 00:05:43.080
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:43.080 --> 00:05:44.600
<v Teacher>Tu has perdido.

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:45.560
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:45.340 --> 00:05:53.420
<v Teacher>So just as <b>me</b> can mean <i>me</i>, or <i>myself</i>, <b>te</b> can mean <i>you</i> or <i>yourself</i>.

00:05:53.420 --> 00:05:56.380
<v Teacher>So how would you say you have got lost?

00:05:56.380 --> 00:05:58.380
<v Teacher>You have lost yourself.

00:05:58.660 --> 00:06:00.100
<v Student><b>Te has perdido</b>.

00:06:00.100 --> 00:06:00.660
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:00.660 --> 00:06:01.940
<v Teacher><b>Te has perdido</b>.

00:06:01.940 --> 00:06:02.980
<v Teacher>Te has perdido.

00:06:02.980 --> 00:06:05.700
<v Teacher>And what if you wanted to be emphatic as well?

00:06:06.420 --> 00:06:08.260
<v Student><b>Tú te has perdido</b>.

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:08.900
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:08.900 --> 00:06:12.180
<v Teacher><b>Tú te has perdido</b>.

00:06:12.180 --> 00:06:13.540
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:06:13.540 --> 00:06:17.140
<v Teacher>What was <i>we have</i>, from <b>haber</b>?

00:06:17.640 --> 00:06:18.520
<v Student><b>Hemos</b>.

00:06:18.520 --> 00:06:19.320
<v Teacher><b>Hemos</b>.

00:06:19.320 --> 00:06:20.040
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:20.040 --> 00:06:22.440
<v Teacher>How would you say we have lost it?

00:06:22.440 --> 00:06:23.720
<v Teacher>We have lost it

00:06:25.640 --> 00:06:28.440
<v Student><b>Lo hemos perdido</b>.

00:06:28.440 --> 00:06:30.200
<v Teacher><b>Lo hemos perdido</b>. Now how would you say <i>we have lost ourselves</i>, or <i>we've got lost</i>?

00:06:30.200 --> 00:06:34.760
<v Student><b>Nos hemos perdido</b>.

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:41.680
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Nos hemos perdido</b>. And what if you wanted to say <i>WE have got lost</i>, <i>WE have lost ourselves</i>?

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:45.280
<v Student><b>Nosotros nos hemos perdido</b>.

00:06:45.280 --> 00:06:53.080
<v Teacher>Good. <b>Nosotros nos hemos perdido</b>. Good.

